	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="R 6457-71 (46)"/>
			<p><!--
Leland B. Morris, Establishment of a Jewish Ghetto in Warsaw, Berlin, 21.10.1940, S. 1f., 6f. Records of the Department of State relating to internal affairs of Poland 1916-1944, Washington 1981 (Mikrofilm-Edition): Dokument 860C.4016/624.--></p>
			<p>The establishment of a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewish</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName> has not been unexpected as reports of some such impending
				action have been current in that city, particularly among <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-246"
					type="subject">Jewish circles</term>, from the early days of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-632" type="subject">occupation</term>. At the same time active <pb n="2"
					facs="R 6457-71 (47)"/> preparations, which could be interpreted in no other way than as tending towards a complete <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-667" type="subject">segregation</term> of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewish population</term>, have been in course for some
				months. [...]</p>
			<pb n="6" facs="R 6457-71 (51)"/>
			<p>A strange commentary on life in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject"
					>German-occupied</term>
				<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName> is presented by the fact that many a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1066" type="subject">nationalist</term>
				<term ref="#ehri_dr_nationalities_poles">Pole</term> has endeavored to take on the ‘protective coloration’ of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jew</term> in order to escape from the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004312">German police</orgName> or to <pb n="7" facs="R 6457-71 (52)"/>
				avoid <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">compulsory labor</term>. These ‘<term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-304" type="subject">refugees</term>’ have adopted <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewish</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject">insignia</term> and taken up residence in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>; many stories are current in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/756135/warsaw.html">Warsaw</placeName> of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> tearing off their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject">racial badges</term> and passing them over in the
				streets to fleeing <term ref="#ehri_dr_nationalities_poles">Poles</term>. It is noteworthy that during the period of anti-Jewish
				disturbances in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Poland</placeName> prior to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject">German occupation</term> the 600,000 people in the
				Jewish district, almost evenly divided between <term ref="#ehri_dr_nationalities_poles">Poles</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term>, managed to get along together peacefully
				and lived in a community spirit which was not noticeable in the other parts of the city. The pending <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-667" type="subject">segregation</term> of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> in an official <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> affects an equal number of <term
					ref="#ehri_dr_nationalities_poles">Poles</term> and the move may in the long run bring greater discomfort to the latter than to
				the majority of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewish population</term>. At any
				rate the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> may well be in a better
				position to maintain a united front towards the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject"
					>occupying authorities</term> and to find in community life a solace and protection until the time comes when a life of freedom
				and tolerance can at last be the lot of the unhappy thousands now to be <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-614" type="subject">concentrated</term> in the greatest of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/7729884/eastern-europe.html">Eastern Europe’s</placeName> many <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewries</term> by an alien conqueror and a ruthless
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-370" type="subject">race enemy</term>.</p>
